-- Gold Gains on Speculation a Weaker Dollar to Spur Demand
-- B y   D e b a r a t i   R o y
-- 2012-08-07T18:01:58Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-08-07/gold-gains-on-speculation-a-weaker-dollar-to-spur-demand.html
Gold declined for the first time in
three sessions in  New York  as signs that European leaders are
making progress to stem the crisis eroded demand for the
precious metal as a haven.  German Chancellor  Angela Merkel ’s government backed the
 European Central Bank ’s bond-buying plan, her deputy spokesman
Georg Streiter said yesterday. The Standard & Poor’s 500 Index
of equities advanced as much as 0.9 percent, while the S&P GSCI
Index of 24 raw materials jumped as much as 1.5 percent.
Estimated total volume of gold contracts traded today was
75,260, compared with a daily average of 188,000 in the seven
months ended July 31.  “There is money flowing into equities and other
commodities in a day of very thin volumes,” Sterling Smith, a
commodity strategist at Citigroup Inc.’s institutional client
group in  Chicago , said in a telephone interview. “People are
favoring more riskier assets today.”  Gold futures for December delivery fell 0.2 percent to
settle at $1,612.80 an ounce at 1:48 p.m. on the Comex in New
York. Prices gained 1.6 percent in the previous two sessions.  Silver futures for September delivery advanced 0.8 percent
to $28.086 an ounce in New York, rising for the third straight
session.  On the  New York Mercantile Exchange , platinum futures for
October delivery gained 0.6 percent to $1,410.40 an ounce.
Palladium futures for September delivery added 1.5 percent to
$588.20 an ounce.  To contact the reporter on this story:
